# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: eye-protection
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:eye-protection/accord-on-fire-and-building-safety-in-bangladesh] The **Accord on Fire and Building Safety in Bangladesh** (the Accord) was signed on 15 May 2013.
[src:eye-protection/accord-on-fire-and-building-safety-in-bangladesh] It is a five-year independent, legally binding agreement between global brands, retailers, and trade unions designed to build a safe and healthy Bangladeshi Ready Made Garment (RMG) Industry.
[src:eye-protection/accord-on-fire-and-building-safety-in-bangladesh] The agreement was created in the immediate aftermath of the Rana Plaza building collapse in Bangladesh that resulted in the death of 1129 people and injured more than 2000.
[src:eye-protection/accord-on-fire-and-building-safety-in-bangladesh] In June 2013, an implementation plan was agreed leading to the incorporation of the Bangladesh Accord Foundation in the Netherlands in October 2013.
[src:eye-protection/accord-on-fire-and-building-safety-in-bangladesh] Worker empowerment through an extensive training program, complaints mechanism and right to refuse unsafe work.
[src:eye-protection/accord-on-fire-and-building-safety-in-bangladesh] The agreement is an example of project-oriented multistakeholder governance.
[src:eye-protection/accord-on-fire-and-building-safety-in-bangladesh] In addition to schemes of building inspection and enforcement of fire and safety standards, the accord requires that contracts by international retailers with Bangladesh manufacturers provide for compensation adequate to maintain safe buildings.
[src:eye-protection/accord-on-fire-and-building-safety-in-bangladesh] Retailers agree to continue to support the Bangladesh textile industry despite possible higher costs.
[src:eye-protection/accord-on-fire-and-building-safety-in-bangladesh] It is estimated that the total cost may be $1 billion, about $500,000 per factory.
[src:eye-protection/accord-on-fire-and-building-safety-in-bangladesh] Close co-operation with the International Labour Organization and the government of Bangladesh is required.
[src:eye-protection/accord-on-fire-and-building-safety-in-bangladesh] A steering committee which governs the accord is established as are dispute resolution procedures such as arbitration.
[src:eye-protection/accord-on-fire-and-building-safety-in-bangladesh] The accord calls for development of an Implementation Plan over 45 days.
[src:eye-protection/accord-on-fire-and-building-safety-in-bangladesh] Prior to the creation of the Accord in 2013, the Bangladesh garment industry had a number of fires and building collapses within the district.
[src:eye-protection/accord-on-fire-and-building-safety-in-bangladesh] In February 2010, a fire in the Garib & Garib Sweater Factory took the lives of 21, while another fire killed 29 more at the “That's It Sportswear” factory in December of the same year.
[src:eye-protection/accord-on-fire-and-building-safety-in-bangladesh] With deaths and buildings collapsing, NGOs in Bangladesh began attempting to work with the major companies involved to approach health and safety concerns within factories.
[src:eye-protection/accord-on-fire-and-building-safety-in-bangladesh] One result of these meetings was the first draft of the Memorandum of Understanding (MoU), intended to prevent these tragedies.
[src:eye-protection/accord-on-fire-and-building-safety-in-bangladesh] Companies such as Gap, PVH Corp., and Tchibo were encouraged to sign the MoU, with Gap becoming unwilling and continuing to employ the same methods of self-checking that had been used prior to the draft of the MoU.
[src:eye-protection/accord-on-fire-and-building-safety-in-bangladesh] Both PVH Corp. and Tchibo signed MoUs with labor rights organizations in 2012 with terms similar to the Bangladesh Accord.
[src:eye-protection/accord-on-fire-and-building-safety-in-bangladesh] Later that same month, a fire at the Tazreen garment factory took the lives of 112 people, with the factory owners facing homicide charges.
[src:eye-protection/accord-on-fire-and-building-safety-in-bangladesh] The German government sponsored a meeting of retailers and NGOs at the beginning of May, and the meeting set a deadline of midnight of 16 May 2013 to sign up to the agreement.
[src:eye-protection/accord-on-fire-and-building-safety-in-bangladesh] Working with the Clean Clothes Campaign, Worker Rights Consortium, International Labor Rights Forum, and the Maquila Solidarity Network, the GIZ agency and IndustriALL (a global union federation) began forming a program that needed to meet the needs of trade union and NGO representatives.
[src:eye-protection/accord-on-fire-and-building-safety-in-bangladesh] The main objectives of this program were a foundation for the Accord on Fire and Building Safety in Bangladesh, specifically focusing on fire safety following the Rana Plaza factory collapse.
[src:eye-protection/accord-on-fire-and-building-safety-in-bangladesh] Based on the previously submitted proposals for safety, the Accord was issued on 5 May 2013, and an official announcement of intention to sign was given by H&M on 13 May 2013.
[src:eye-protection/accord-on-fire-and-building-safety-in-bangladesh] H&M signing of the Accord was a key step in encouraging other companies to declare their intent to sign as well.
[src:eye-protection/accord-on-fire-and-building-safety-in-bangladesh] Numerous companies had signed up by the deadline, covering over 1,000 Bangladeshi garment factories.
[src:eye-protection/accord-on-fire-and-building-safety-in-bangladesh] Since 29 October 2013, the Accord has been signed by over 200 apparel brands, retailers and importers from over 20 countries in Europe, North America, Asia and Australia; two global trade unions; and eight Bangladesh trade unions and four NGO witnesses.
[src:eye-protection/accord-on-fire-and-building-safety-in-bangladesh] Some of the notable companies are listed below.
[src:eye-protection/accord-on-fire-and-building-safety-in-bangladesh] For a complete list see the Bangladesh Accord website.
[src:eye-protection/accord-on-fire-and-building-safety-in-bangladesh] Most North American retailers did not sign the accord.
[src:eye-protection/accord-on-fire-and-building-safety-in-bangladesh] Companies like Gap Inc. and Walmart cited liability concerns.
[src:eye-protection/accord-on-fire-and-building-safety-in-bangladesh] Coffee, professor of corporate law at Columbia Law School, pointed out, *Kiobel v.
[src:eye-protection/accord-on-fire-and-building-safety-in-bangladesh] Royal Dutch Petroleum Co.* might apply thus foreclosing suits by Bangladesh workers under the Alien Tort Claims Act, but this seems unlikely.
[src:eye-protection/accord-on-fire-and-building-safety-in-bangladesh] It is more likely that liability would be based on contract law.
[src:eye-protection/accord-on-fire-and-building-safety-in-bangladesh] On 10 July 2013, a group of 17 major North American retailers calling themselves the Alliance for Bangladesh Worker Safety announced the Bangladesh Worker Safety Initiative.
[src:eye-protection/accord-on-fire-and-building-safety-in-bangladesh] The Initiative drew criticism from labour groups who complained that it was less stringent than the Accord and lacked legally binding commitments to pay for improvements.
[src:eye-protection/accord-on-fire-and-building-safety-in-bangladesh] There were a significant number of accomplishments under the 2013 Accord, those of which included large scale hazard identification and remediation of these safety issues.
[src:eye-protection/accord-on-fire-and-building-safety-in-bangladesh] Engineers inspected more than 2000 RMG factories where they identified more than 150,000 safety hazards.
[src:eye-protection/accord-on-fire-and-building-safety-in-bangladesh] Additionally, companies committed to negotiating terms with their suppliers such that it was possible for the factories to maintain and uphold a safe workplace environment along with maintaining the safety remediation requirements.
[src:eye-protection/accord-on-fire-and-building-safety-in-bangladesh] There was also a Safety Training Program initiative where 1.4 million workers in Accord-covered factories were educated and informed about proper workplace safety and evacuation drills, along with the rights that they had under the Accord.
[src:eye-protection/accord-on-fire-and-building-safety-in-bangladesh] Anything that was not effectively handled at the factory level, such as individual worker complaints, were processed through Safety and Health Complaints Mechanism, which allowed them to remedy these concerns.
[src:eye-protection/accord-on-fire-and-building-safety-in-bangladesh] By the end of the 2013 Accord, 200 worker complaints had been effectively handed through this program.
[src:eye-protection/accord-on-fire-and-building-safety-in-bangladesh] As of September 2019, there has been a 90% initial remediation progress rate at Accord-covered factories.
[src:eye-protection/accord-on-fire-and-building-safety-in-bangladesh] 254 factories have completed the initial remediation and there has been over 90% initial remediation at 1,120 factories.
[src:eye-protection/accord-on-fire-and-building-safety-in-bangladesh] The 2018 Transition Key Accord was signed on 1 July 2018, in order to fulfill the same purposes as the 2013 Accord as well as maintaining the progress previously made.
[src:eye-protection/accord-on-fire-and-building-safety-in-bangladesh] It is also a legally binding agreement between brands and trade unions and some of the key features include brand commitment to ensure safety remediation is completed and financially feasible, independent safety inspections and remediation program.
[src:eye-protection/accord-on-fire-and-building-safety-in-bangladesh] There will also be disclosure of inspection reports and corrective action plans.
[src:eye-protection/accord-on-fire-and-building-safety-in-bangladesh] Other key features of the accord include: a Safety Committee and Training Program, Safety and Health Complaints Mechanism, protection of right to refuse unsafe work, along with the transition of the Accord functions to a larger national safety monitoring body.
[src:eye-protection/accord-on-fire-and-building-safety-in-bangladesh] The Accord is governed by a Steering Committee that consists of representatives from the signatory companies and trade unions along with a neutral chair from the International Labor Organization (ILO).
[src:eye-protection/accord-on-fire-and-building-safety-in-bangladesh] One of the key features of the 2018 Accord is that it has pledged to hand over its functions to the Bangladesh government's Remediation and Coordination Cell (RCC), a unit of the Department of Inspection for Factories and Establishments.
[src:eye-protection/accord-on-fire-and-building-safety-in-bangladesh] The 2018 Accord pledges support for the RCC until it fully takes over the Accord functions.
[src:eye-protection/accord-on-fire-and-building-safety-in-bangladesh] The transition started gradually, with the RCC taking on some of the inspection and remediation duties at factories.
[src:eye-protection/acrodynia] Besides peripheral neuropathy (presenting as paresthesia or itching, burning or pain) and discoloration, swelling (edema) and desquamation may occur.
[src:eye-protection/acrodynia] Since mercury blocks the degradation pathway of catecholamines, epinephrine excess causes profuse sweating (diaphora), tachycardia, salivation and elevated blood pressure.
[src:eye-protection/acrodynia] Mercury is suggested to inactivate S-adenosyl-methionine, which is necessary for catecholamine catabolism by catechol-o-methyl transferase.
[src:eye-protection/acrodynia] Affected children may show red cheeks and nose, red (erythematous) lips, loss of hair, teeth, and nails, transient rashes, hypotonia and photophobia.
[src:eye-protection/acrodynia] Other symptoms may include kidney dysfunction (e.g.
[src:eye-protection/acrodynia] Fanconi syndrome) or neuropsychiatric symptoms (emotional lability, memory impairment, insomnia).
[src:eye-protection/acrodynia] Thus, the clinical presentation may resemble pheochromocytoma or Kawasaki disease.
[src:eye-protection/acrodynia] There is some evidence that the same mercury poisoning may predispose to Young's syndrome (men with bronchiectasis and low sperm count).
[src:eye-protection/acrodynia] Mercury compounds like calomel were historically used for various medical purposes: as laxatives, diuretics, antiseptics or antimicrobial drugs for syphilis, typhus and yellow fever.
[src:eye-protection/acrodynia] Teething powders were a widespread source of mercury poisoning until the recognition of mercury toxicity in the 1940s.
[src:eye-protection/acrodynia] However, mercury poisoning and acrodynia still exist today.
[src:eye-protection/acrodynia] Modern sources of mercury intoxication include broken thermometers.
[src:eye-protection/acrodynia] Removal of the inciting agent is the goal of treatment.
[src:eye-protection/acrodynia] Correcting fluid and electrolyte losses and rectifying any nutritional imbalances (vitamin-rich diets, vitamin-B complex) are of utmost importance in the treatment of the disease.
[src:eye-protection/acrodynia] The chelating agent meso 2,3-dimercaptosuccinic acid has been shown to be the preferred treatment modality.
[src:eye-protection/acrodynia] It can almost completely prevent methylmercury uptake by erythrocytes and hepatocytes.
[src:eye-protection/acrodynia] In the past, dimercaprol (British antilewisite; 2,3-dimer-capto-l-propanol) and D-penicillamine were the most popular treatment modalities.
[src:eye-protection/acrodynia] Disodium edetate (Versene) was also used.
[src:eye-protection/acrodynia] Neither disodium edetate nor British antilewisite has proven reliable.
[src:eye-protection/acrodynia] British antilewisite has now been shown to increase CNS levels and exacerbate toxicity.
[src:eye-protection/acrodynia] N -acetyl-penicillamine has been successfully given to patients with mercury-induced neuropathies and chronic toxicity, although it is not approved for such uses.
[src:eye-protection/acrodynia] It has a less favorable adverse effect profile than meso 2,3-dimercaptosuccinic acid.
[src:eye-protection/acrodynia] Hemodialysis with and without the addition of L-cysteine as a chelating agent has been used in some patients experiencing acute kidney injury from mercury toxicity.
[src:eye-protection/acrodynia] Peritoneal dialysis and plasma exchange also may be of benefit.
[src:eye-protection/acrodynia] Tolazoline (Priscoline) has been shown to offer symptomatic relief from sympathetic overactivity.
[src:eye-protection/acrodynia] Antibiotics are necessary when massive hyperhidrosis, which may rapidly lead to miliaria rubra, is present.
[src:eye-protection/acrodynia] This can easily progress to bacterial secondary infection with a tendency for ulcerating pyoderma.
[src:eye-protection/administrative-controls] In the hierarchy of hazard controls, administrative controls lies 4th below engineering controls and above personal protective equipment in terms of the effectiveness and efficiency of hazard controls ranking.
[src:eye-protection/administrative-controls] They should be used after elimination, substitution and engineering controls have already been implemented / considered or as an extra layer of protection from hazards.
[src:eye-protection/administrative-controls] Some agencies add isolation as a step to their hierarchy of controls, with that level also needing consideration prior to administrative controls.
[src:eye-protection/administrative-controls] The reasoning for lower effectiveness is that success in reducing hazards relies on individuals following rules, procedures, and/or training, all of which are still susceptible to human error, while levels above it reduce the impact of human error.
[src:eye-protection/administrative-controls] Administrative controls are more effective than PPE because they involve some manner of prior planning and avoidance, whereas PPE serves only as a final barrier between the hazard and worker.
[src:eye-protection/administrative-controls] Administrative controls are second lowest because they require workers or employers to actively think or comply with regulations and do not offer permanent solutions to problems.
[src:eye-protection/administrative-controls] Generally, administrative controls are cheaper to begin, but they may become more expensive over time as higher failure rates and the need for constant training or re-certification outweigh the initial investments of the three more desirable hazard controls in the hierarchy.
[src:eye-protection/administrative-controls] National Institute for Occupational Safety and Health recommends administrative controls when hazards cannot be removed or changed, and engineering controls are not practical.
[src:eye-protection/administrative-controls] Some common examples of administrative controls include work practice controls such as prohibiting mouth pipetting and rotating worker shifts in coal mines to prevent hearing loss.
[src:eye-protection/administrative-controls] Other examples include hours of service regulations for commercial vehicle operators, safety signage for hazards, regular maintenance of equipment, and incorporating stretching and short breaks to reduce ergonomic stressors.
[src:eye-protection/administrative-controls] Administrative controls are used to limit the spread of COVID-19 by changing human habits and social organization.
[src:eye-protection/administrative-controls] These include policies such as remote work, restriction on indoor gatherings, staggered schedules, enforcing masks in areas and mandating vaccination while reducing close contact and crowding.
[src:eye-protection/administrative-controls] The effectiveness of these actions are highly dependent on human behavior, making them less reliable on their own, but when combined with engineering controls such as hard barricades for maintaining distance or limiting the entry by controlling doors, then they can be highly effective.
[src:eye-protection/administrative-controls] The origin of administrative controls goes to the ancient governance systems where rulers used written rules and organized bureaucracies to maintain order and efficiency.
[src:eye-protection/administrative-controls] Early examples can be found from Mesopotamia, China, and Egypt where officials managed labor, justice, and even the work schedules to reduce stress.
[src:eye-protection/administrative-controls] Administrative control methods were also used during the industrial revolution as a way to reduce growing injuries by setting up rules, supervision, and procedures.
[src:eye-protection/administrative-controls] By the 20th century, administrative measures like work scheduling, training, and enforcing exposure limits became common for managing risk.
[src:eye-protection/administrative-controls] The formation of OSHA and NIOSH in 1970 marked a major step in formalizing such controls in the US workforce over time, evolving to focus on systematic risk management, accountability and continuous improvement.
[src:eye-protection/adventure-racing] The roots of adventure racing are deep and the origin of the modern adventure race is debatable.
[src:eye-protection/adventure-racing] Some point to the two-day Karrimor International Mountain Marathon, first held in 1968 as the birth of modern adventure racing.
[src:eye-protection/adventure-racing] The Karrimor Marathon required two-person teams to traverse mountainous terrain while carrying all the supplies required to support themselves through the double-length marathon run.
[src:eye-protection/adventure-racing] In 1980, the Alpine Ironman was held in New Zealand.
[src:eye-protection/adventure-racing] Individual competitors ran, paddled, and skied toward a distant finish line.
[src:eye-protection/adventure-racing] Later that year, the Alpine Ironman's creator, Robin Judkins launched the better-known Coast to Coast race.
[src:eye-protection/adventure-racing] This involved most of the elements of modern adventure racing: trail running, cycling and paddling.
[src:eye-protection/adventure-racing] Australia's two-day WildTrek ran from 1981 through 2005.
[src:eye-protection/adventure-racing] Independently in 1982, the first expedition-length adventure race, a week-long, North American event called the Alaska Mountain Wilderness Classic debuted.
[src:eye-protection/adventure-racing] It involved wilderness travel—no roads, no pack animals, and no support team to carry food and equipment from start to finish—with less than 50 of its 150-mile length on a trail.
[src:eye-protection/adventure-racing] It continues today, changing courses every three years.
[src:eye-protection/adventure-racing] In 1989, the modern era of adventure racing arrived with Gerald Fusil's launch of the Raid Gauloises in New Zealand.
[src:eye-protection/adventure-racing] Inspired by the Paris-Dakar Rally, Fusil envisioned an expanded expedition-style race in which competitors would rely on their own strength and abilities to traverse great and challenging terrain.
[src:eye-protection/adventure-racing] The race included all the modern elements of adventure racing, including mixed-gender teams competing in a multi-day 400+ mile race.
[src:eye-protection/adventure-racing] Building on Fusil's concept, the inaugural Southern Traverse was held in 1991.
[src:eye-protection/adventure-racing] In the early 1990s, Mark Burnett read a *Los Angeles Times* article about Raid Gauloises and was inspired to compete and bring the race to the USA and promote the race as a major televised sporting event.
[src:eye-protection/adventure-racing] After purchasing the rights from Gerald Fusil, Burnett launched the first "Eco-Challenge" race in 1995.
[src:eye-protection/adventure-racing] Burnett promoted his event with Emmy-award-winning films (tapping the talent of Mike Sears to produce the films for the first two events).
[src:eye-protection/adventure-racing] This incarnation of Eco-Challenge was last held in 2002 when Burnett shifted his focus to Survivor, the Contender, the Apprentice and other reality-based television shows.
[src:eye-protection/adventure-racing] With the Eco-Challenge also came the name "adventure race", a phrase coined by journalist and author Martin Dugard, to describe the class of races embodied by the Raid and Eco-Challenge.
[src:eye-protection/adventure-racing] The United States Adventure Racing Association "USARA" was formed in 1998.
[src:eye-protection/adventure-racing] The USARA was the first "national governing body" for the sport of adventure racing and arose from the need for safety standards, insurance and to promote the growth of adventure racing in the United States.
[src:eye-protection/adventure-racing] USARA has added national rankings, a national championship, and ecological standards to the list of benefits provided for the sport of adventure racing.
[src:eye-protection/adventure-racing] In 2000, the inaugural United States Adventure Racing Association Adventure Race National Championship was held in Kernville, California.
[src:eye-protection/adventure-racing] The USARA National Championship is typically held the first weekend in October and is considered the premier adventure race in the U.S.
[src:eye-protection/adventure-racing] The USARA Adventure Racing National Championship has continued each year drawing the best US teams for a chance at earning the title of national champion.
[src:eye-protection/adventure-racing] The National Points Series Champion is also awarded at the National Championship.
[src:eye-protection/adventure-racing] In 2001, the inaugural World Championships were held in Switzerland with Team Nokia Adventure crossing the finishing line first.
[src:eye-protection/adventure-racing] The concept of a world championship lay dormant until it was revived in 2004, with Canada's Raid the North Extreme serving as the AR World Championship event in Newfoundland and Labrador.
[src:eye-protection/adventure-racing] The Adventure Racing World Series and its ultimate event, the AR World Championships have been held every year since.
[src:eye-protection/adventure-racing] The 2013 World Championships were in Costa Rica, 2014 in Ecuador, 2015 in Brazil, 2016 in Australia, 2017 in the United States, and 2018 off the coast of Africa on the Reunion Island.
[src:eye-protection/adventure-racing] In 2004, professional geologist Stjepan Pavicic organized the first Patagonian Expedition Race at the bottom tip of the American continent, in the Chilean Tierra del Fuego.
[src:eye-protection/adventure-racing] Truly demanding routes through rough terrain of often more than 600 km soon made it be known as "the last wild race".
[src:eye-protection/adventure-racing] In 2010, the German Adventure Race Series was held for the first time in three different locations all over Germany.
[src:eye-protection/adventure-racing] Since then the popularity of the sport in Germany has grown every year.
[src:eye-protection/adventure-racing] More races and venues have joined the series and the number of competitors are still growing from year to year.
[src:eye-protection/adventure-racing] Competitors can start in teams of two (male, female or mixed) within the categories Master (15–20 h), Challenger (8–10 h) or Beginner (4–6 h).
[src:eye-protection/adventure-racing] In 2010 in Australia, Adventure Junkie company was launched.
[src:eye-protection/adventure-racing] It formed a grassroots movement to help promote and expand the sport of Adventure Racing in Australia.
[src:eye-protection/adventure-racing] They have started a series of short sprint races and longer expedition-style events up to 48-hour events.
[src:eye-protection/adventure-racing] In 2012, Commander Forer of the Royal Navy organized the first Sea-land navigation discipline race the Solent Amphibious Challenge.
[src:eye-protection/adventure-racing] The race demanded the competitors split up between sailing, running, and cycling in parts of the race and rendezvous at the end, and sail the yacht to the finish line.
[src:eye-protection/adventure-racing] In December 2017, the Adventure Racing Cooperative (ARC) was launched in the United States.
[src:eye-protection/adventure-racing] It was formed in a grassroots movement to help promote and expand the sport of Adventure Racing in the United States.
[src:eye-protection/adventure-racing] ARC is a 501(c)(3) not-for-profit business.
[src:eye-protection/adventure-racing] In December 2018 launched Warrior Adventure Racing in the US and has become one the largest event groups in the World with adventure races like the famous "Sea to Sea Expedition Race" across Florida, Expedition Alaska and Expedition Colorado.
[src:eye-protection/adventure-racing] The majority of adventure races include trail running, mountain biking, and a paddling event.
[src:eye-protection/adventure-racing] Navigation and rope work are also featured in all but the shortest races.
[src:eye-protection/adventure-travel] Adventure tourists may have the motivation to achieve mental states characterized as rush or flow, resulting from stepping outside their comfort zone.
[src:eye-protection/adventure-travel] This may be from experiencing culture shock or by performing acts requiring significant effort and involve some degree of risk, real or perceived, or physical danger.
[src:eye-protection/adventure-travel] This may include activities such as mountaineering, trekking, bungee jumping, mountain biking, cycling, canoeing, scuba diving, rafting, kayaking, zip-lining, paragliding, hiking, exploring, Geocaching, canyoneering, river trekking, sandboarding, caving and rock climbing.
[src:eye-protection/adventure-travel] Some obscure forms of adventure travel include disaster and ghetto tourism.
[src:eye-protection/adventure-travel] Other rising forms of adventure travel include social and jungle tourism.
[src:eye-protection/adventure-travel] Access to inexpensive consumer technology, with respect to Global Positioning Systems, flashpacking, social networking and photography, have increased the worldwide interest in adventure travel.
[src:eye-protection/adventure-travel] The interest in independent adventure travel has also increased as more specialist travel websites emerge offering previously niche locations and sports.
[src:eye-protection/adventure-travel] Adventure sports tourism has traditionally been dominated by men.
[src:eye-protection/adventure-travel] Although women's participation has grown, the gender gap is still pronounced in terms of quantitative engagement in these forms of sport tourism.
[src:eye-protection/adventure-travel] Since ancient times, humans have traveled in search for food and skills of survival, but have also engaged in adventurous travel, in explorations of sea lanes, a destination, or even a new country.
[src:eye-protection/adventure-travel] Adventurer travelers began to push to the limits, with the mountaineering of Matterhorn in 1865 and the river rafting on the Colorado River in 1869.
[src:eye-protection/adventure-travel] Shortly after, two key institutions were formed, including the National Geographic Society and the Explorers Club, which continue to support adventure travel.
[src:eye-protection/adventure-travel] At the end of World War II, modern adventure began to take off, with the 1950 French Annapurna expedition and the 1953 British Mount Everest expedition.
[src:eye-protection/adventure-travel] Today, it remains a niche of travel and a fast-changing sector with new variants of activities for a travel experience.
[src:eye-protection/adventure-travel] There is a trend for developing tourism specifically for disabled people.
[src:eye-protection/adventure-travel] Adventure travel for disabled people has become a US$13 billion a year industry in North America.
[src:eye-protection/adventure-travel] Some adventure travel destinations offer diverse programs and job opportunities developed specifically for the disabled.
[src:eye-protection/adventure-travel] Extreme tourism involves travel to dangerous (*extreme*) locations or participation in dangerous events or activities.
[src:eye-protection/adventure-travel] This form of tourism can overlap with extreme sport.
[src:eye-protection/adventure-travel] Travelling to locations far away from human settlements and/or infrastructure.
[src:eye-protection/adventure-travel] Could be close to big city (few hours drive) in terms of straight line distance, but reaching the location requires a long period of time and/or a large amount of effort.
[src:eye-protection/adventure-travel] Self sufficiency required, as it's difficult to get timely help or rescue in an emergency.
[src:eye-protection/adventure-travel] Jungle tourism is a subcategory of adventure travel defined by active multifaceted physical means of travel in the jungle regions of the earth.
[src:eye-protection/adventure-travel] According to the Glossary of Tourism Terms, jungle tours have become a major component of green tourism in tropical destinations and are a relatively recent phenomenon of Western international tourism.
[src:eye-protection/adventure-travel] Overland travel or overlanding refers to an overland journey – perhaps originating with Marco Polo's first overland expedition in the 13th century from Venice to the Mongolian court of Kublai Khan.
[src:eye-protection/adventure-travel] Today overlanding is a form of extended adventure holiday, embarking on a long journey, often in a group.
[src:eye-protection/adventure-travel] Overland companies provide a converted truck or a bus plus a tour leader, and the group travels together overland for a period of weeks or months.
[src:eye-protection/adventure-travel] Since the 1960s overlanding has been a popular means of travel between destinations across Africa, Europe, Asia (particularly India), the Americas and Australia.
[src:eye-protection/adventure-travel] The "Hippie trail" of the 60s and 70s saw thousands of young westerners travelling through the Middle East to India and Nepal.
[src:eye-protection/adventure-travel] Many of the older traditional routes are still active, along with newer routes like Iceland to South Africa overland and Central Asian post soviet states.
[src:eye-protection/adventure-travel] Scuba diving is a sport in which participants explore underwater places while inhaling compressed air from tanks.
[src:eye-protection/adventure-travel] Scuba diving is most popular in locations with tropical coral reefs, but it may be found in almost any location with water.
[src:eye-protection/adventure-travel] "Rush as a key motivation in skilled adventure tourism: Resolving the risk recreation paradox".
[src:eye-protection/adventure-travel] *Centers for Disease Control and Prevention*.
[src:eye-protection/adventure-travel] Archived from the original on 13 October 2007.
[src:eye-protection/adventure-travel] Apollo, M., Mostowska, J., Legut, A., Maciuk, K., & Timothy, D.
[src:eye-protection/adventure-travel] Gender differences in competitive adventure sports tourism.
[src:eye-protection/aerosol] An **aerosol** is a suspension of fine solid particles or liquid droplets in air or another gas.
[src:eye-protection/aerosol] Aerosols can be generated from natural or human causes.
[src:eye-protection/aerosol] The scientific term *aerosol* refers to the mixture of particulates in gas, and not to the particulate matter alone.
[src:eye-protection/aerosol] The liquid or solid particles in an aerosol have diameters typically less than 1 μm.
[src:eye-protection/aerosol] Larger particles with a significant settling speed make the mixture a suspension, although the distinction is not clear.
[src:eye-protection/aerosol] Examples of natural aerosols are fog, mist, and dust from geological or biological sources.
[src:eye-protection/aerosol] Certain infections spread by means of small droplets in the breath, sometimes called bioaerosols.
[src:eye-protection/aerosol] Several types of atmospheric aerosol have a significant effect on Earth's climate: volcanic, desert dust, sea-salt, originating from biogenic sources and human-made.
[src:eye-protection/aerosol] Volcanic aerosol forms in the stratosphere after an eruption as droplets of sulfuric acid that can prevail for up to two years, and reflect sunlight, lowering temperature.
[src:eye-protection/aerosol] Desert dust, mineral particles blown to high altitudes, absorb heat and may be responsible for inhibiting storm cloud formation.
[src:eye-protection/aerosol] In everyday language, *aerosol* often refers to a dispensing system that delivers a consumer product from a spray can.
[src:eye-protection/aerosol] Other examples of human caused aerosols include perfume from atomizers, medical treatments for respiratory illnesses, dust from material or industrial sources, smoke, irrigation mist, sprayed pesticides, particulate air pollutants, and mist from the discharge at hydroelectric dams.
[src:eye-protection/aerosol] Human-made sulfate aerosols, primarily from burning oil and coal, affect the behavior of clouds.
[src:eye-protection/aerosol] When aerosols absorb pollutants, it facilitates the deposition of pollutants to the surface of the earth as well as to bodies of water.
[src:eye-protection/aerosol] This has the potential to be damaging to both the environment and human health.
[src:eye-protection/aerosol] Ship tracks are clouds that form around the exhaust released by ships into the still ocean air.
[src:eye-protection/aerosol] Water molecules collect around the tiny particles (aerosols) from exhaust to form a cloud seed.
[src:eye-protection/aerosol] More and more water accumulates on the seed until a visible cloud is formed.
[src:eye-protection/aerosol] In the case of ship tracks, the cloud seeds are stretched over a long narrow path where the wind has blown the ship's exhaust, so the resulting clouds resemble long strings over the ocean.
[src:eye-protection/aerosol] The warming caused by human-produced greenhouse gases has been somewhat offset by the cooling effect of human-produced aerosols.
[src:eye-protection/aerosol] In 2020, regulations on fuel significantly cut sulfur dioxide emissions from international shipping by approximately 80%, leading to an unexpected global geoengineering termination shock.
[src:eye-protection/aerosol] Aerosol is defined as a suspension system of solid or liquid particles in a gas.
[src:eye-protection/aerosol] An aerosol includes both the particles and the suspending gas, which is usually air.
[src:eye-protection/aerosol] Meteorologists and climatologists often refer to them as particle matter, while the classification in sizes ranges like PM2.5 or PM10, is useful in the field of atmospheric pollution as these size range play a role in ascertain the harmful effects in human health.
[src:eye-protection/aerosol] Donnan presumably first used the term *aerosol* during World War I to describe an aero-solution, clouds of microscopic particles in air.
[src:eye-protection/aerosol] This term developed analogously to the term hydrosol, a colloid system with water as the dispersed medium.
[src:eye-protection/aerosol] *Primary aerosols* contain particles introduced directly into the gas; *secondary aerosols* form through gas-to-particle conversion.
[src:eye-protection/aerosol] Key aerosol groups include sulfates, organic carbon, black carbon, nitrates, mineral dust, and sea salt, they usually clump together to form a complex mixture.
[src:eye-protection/aerosol] Various types of aerosol, classified according to physical form and how they were generated, include dust, fume, mist, smoke and fog.
[src:eye-protection/aerosol] There are several measures of aerosol concentration.
[src:eye-protection/aerosol] Environmental science and environmental health often use the *mass concentration* (*M*), defined as the mass of particulate matter per unit volume, in units such as μg/m3.
[src:eye-protection/aerosol] Also commonly used is the *number concentration* (*N*), the number of particles per unit volume, in units such as number per m3 or number per cm3.
[src:eye-protection/aerosol] Particle size has a major influence on particle properties, and the aerosol particle radius or diameter (*dp*) is a key property used to characterise aerosols.
[src:eye-protection/aerosol] A *monodisperse* aerosol, producible in the laboratory, contains particles of uniform size.
[src:eye-protection/aerosol] Most aerosols, however, as *polydisperse* colloidal systems, exhibit a range of particle sizes.
[src:eye-protection/aerosol] Liquid droplets are almost always nearly spherical, but scientists use an *equivalent diameter* to characterize the properties of various shapes of solid particles, some very irregular.
[src:eye-protection/aerosol] The equivalent diameter is the diameter of a spherical particle with the same value of some physical property as the irregular particle.
[src:eye-protection/aerosol] The *equivalent volume diameter* (*de*) is defined as the diameter of a sphere of the same volume as that of the irregular particle.
[src:eye-protection/aerosol] Also commonly used is the aerodynamic diameter, *da*.
[src:eye-protection/aerosol] Several types of atmospheric aerosol have a significant effect on Earth's climate: volcanic, desert dust, sea-salt, that originating from biogenic sources and human-made.
[src:eye-protection/aerosol] Although all hydrometeors, solid and liquid, can be described as aerosols, a distinction is commonly made between such dispersions (i.e. clouds and precipitation) containing relatively large water drops or ice crystals, and aerosol particles.
[src:eye-protection/aerosol] The presence of aerosols in the Earth's atmosphere can influence its climate, as well as human health.
[src:eye-protection/aerosol] Volcanic eruptions release large amounts of sulphuric acid, hydrogen sulfide and hydrochloric acid into the atmosphere.
[src:eye-protection/aerosol] These gases represent aerosols and eventually return to earth as acid rain, having a number of adverse effects on the environment and human life.
[src:eye-protection/aerosol] Aerosols interact with the Earth's energy budget in two ways, directly and indirectly.
[src:eye-protection/aerosol] Aerosol particles with an effective diameter smaller than 10 μm can enter the bronchi, while the ones with an effective diameter smaller than 2.5 μm can enter as far as the gas exchange region in the lungs, which can be hazardous to human health.
[src:eye-protection/aerosol] For a monodisperse aerosol, a single number—the particle diameter—suffices to describe the size of the particles.
[src:eye-protection/aerosol] However, more complicated particle-size distributions describe the sizes of the particles in a polydisperse aerosol.
[src:eye-protection/aerosol] This distribution defines the relative amounts of particles, sorted according to size.
[src:eye-protection/aerosol] One approach to defining the particle size distribution uses a list of the sizes of every particle in a sample.
[src:eye-protection/aerosol] However, this approach proves tedious to ascertain in aerosols with millions of particles and awkward to use.
[src:eye-protection/aerosol] Another approach splits the size range into intervals and finds the number (or proportion) of particles in each interval.
[src:eye-protection/aerosol] The particle size distribution can be approximated.
[src:eye-protection/aerosol] The normal distribution usually does not suitably describe particle size distributions in aerosols because of the skewness associated with a long tail of larger particles.
[src:eye-protection/aerosol] Also for a quantity that varies over a large range, as many aerosol sizes do, the width of the distribution implies negative particles sizes, which is not physically realistic.
[src:eye-protection/aerosol] However, the normal distribution can be suitable for some aerosols, such as test aerosols, certain pollen grains and spores.
[src:eye-protection/aerosol] The log-normal distribution has no negative values, can cover a wide range of values, and fits many observed size distributions reasonably well.
[src:eye-protection/aerosol] For low values of the Reynolds number (<1), true for most aerosol motion, Stokes' law describes the force of resistance on a solid spherical particle in a fluid.
[src:eye-protection/aerosol] However, Stokes' law is only valid when the velocity of the gas at the surface of the particle is zero.
[src:eye-protection/aerosol] For small particles (< 1 μm) that characterize aerosols, however, this assumption fails.
[src:eye-protection/aerosol] To account for this failure, one can introduce the Cunningham correction factor, always greater than 1.
[src:eye-protection/aerosol] This allows us to calculate the terminal velocity of a particle undergoing gravitational settling in still air.
[src:eye-protection/aerosol] is the terminal settling velocity of the particle.
[src:eye-protection/aerosol] The terminal velocity can also be derived for other kinds of forces.
[src:eye-protection/aerosol] If Stokes' law holds, then the resistance to motion is directly proportional to speed.
[src:eye-protection/aerosol] To account for the effect of the shape of non-spherical particles, a correction factor known as the *dynamic shape factor* is applied to Stokes' law.
[src:eye-protection/aerosol] The aerodynamic diameter of an irregular particle is defined as the diameter of the spherical particle with a density of 1000 kg/m3 and the same settling velocity as the irregular particle.
[src:eye-protection/aerosol] One can apply the aerodynamic diameter to particulate pollutants or to inhaled drugs to predict where in the respiratory tract such particles deposit.
[src:eye-protection/aerosol] Pharmaceutical companies typically use aerodynamic diameter, not geometric diameter, to characterize particles in inhalable drugs.
[src:eye-protection/aerosol] The previous discussion focused on single aerosol particles.
[src:eye-protection/aerosol] In contrast, *aerosol dynamics* explains the evolution of complete aerosol populations.
[src:eye-protection/aerosol] The concentrations of particles will change over time as a result of many processes.
[src:eye-protection/aerosol] External processes that move particles outside a volume of gas under study include diffusion, gravitational settling, and electric charges and other external forces that cause particle migration.
[src:eye-protection/aerosol] A second set of processes internal to a given volume of gas include particle formation (nucleation), evaporation, chemical reaction, and coagulation.
[src:eye-protection/aerosol] A differential equation called the *Aerosol General Dynamic Equation* (GDE) characterizes the evolution of the number density of particles in an aerosol due to these processes.
[src:eye-protection/aerosol] As particles and droplets in an aerosol collide with one another, they may undergo coalescence or aggregation.
[src:eye-protection/aerosol] This process leads to a change in the aerosol particle-size distribution, with the mode increasing in diameter as total number of particles decreases.
[src:eye-protection/aerosol] On occasion, particles may shatter apart into numerous smaller particles; however, this process usually occurs primarily in particles too large for consideration as aerosols.
[src:eye-protection/aerosol] where $\lambda$ is the mean free path of the suspending gas and d is the diameter of the particle.
[src:eye-protection/aerosol] For particles in the *free molecular regime*, *Kn* >> 1; particles small compared to the mean free path of the suspending gas.
[src:eye-protection/aerosol] In this regime, particles interact with the suspending gas through a series of "ballistic" collisions with gas molecules.
[src:eye-protection/aerosol] As such, they behave similarly to gas molecules, tending to follow streamlines and diffusing rapidly through Brownian motion.
[src:eye-protection/aerosol] where *a* is the particle radius, *P*∞ and *PA* are the pressures far from the droplet and at the surface of the droplet respectively, *kb* is the Boltzmann constant, *T* is the temperature, *CA* is mean thermal velocity and *α* is mass accommodation coefficient.
[src:eye-protection/aerosol] The derivation of this equation assumes constant pressure and constant diffusion coefficient.
[src:eye-protection/aerosol] Particles are in the *continuum regime* when Kn << 1.
[src:eye-protection/aerosol] In this regime, the particles are big compared to the mean free path of the suspending gas, meaning that the suspending gas acts as a continuous fluid flowing round the particle.
[src:eye-protection/aerosol] The *transition regime* contains all the particles in between the free molecular and continuum regimes or *Kn* ≈ 1.
[src:eye-protection/aerosol] The forces experienced by a particle are a complex combination of interactions with individual gas molecules and macroscopic interactions.
[src:eye-protection/aerosol] where *I*cont is the mass flux in the continuum regime.
[src:eye-protection/aerosol] This formula is called the Fuchs-Sutugin interpolation formula.
[src:eye-protection/aerosol] These equations do not take into account the heat release effect.
[src:eye-protection/aerosol] Aerosol partitioning theory governs condensation on and evaporation from an aerosol surface, respectively.
[src:eye-protection/aerosol] Condensation of mass causes the mode of the particle-size distributions of the aerosol to increase; conversely, evaporation causes the mode to decrease.
[src:eye-protection/aerosol] Nucleation is the process of forming aerosol mass from the condensation of a gaseous precursor, specifically a vapor.
[src:eye-protection/aerosol] Net condensation of the vapor requires supersaturation, a partial pressure greater than its vapor pressure.
[src:eye-protection/aerosol] Chemical reactions may increase the partial pressure of a gas or lower its vapor pressure.
[src:eye-protection/aerosol] The addition of additional vapor to the system may lower the equilibrium vapor pressure according to Raoult's law.
[src:eye-protection/aerosol] There are two types of nucleation processes.
[src:eye-protection/aerosol] Gases preferentially condense onto surfaces of pre-existing aerosol particles, known as **heterogeneous nucleation**.
[src:eye-protection/aerosol] This process causes the diameter at the mode of particle-size distribution to increase with constant number concentration.
[src:eye-protection/aerosol] With sufficiently high supersaturation and no suitable surfaces, particles may condense in the absence of a pre-existing surface, known as **homogeneous nucleation**.
[src:eye-protection/aerosol] This results in the addition of very small, rapidly growing particles to the particle-size distribution.
[src:eye-protection/aerosol] Water coats particles in aerosols, making them *activated*, usually in the context of forming a cloud droplet (such as natural cloud seeding by aerosols from trees in a forest).
[src:eye-protection/aerosol] Following the Kelvin equation (based on the curvature of liquid droplets), smaller particles need a higher ambient relative humidity to maintain equilibrium than larger particles do.
[src:eye-protection/aerosol] where $p_{s}$ is the saturation vapor pressure above a particle at equilibrium (around a curved liquid droplet), *p*0 is the saturation vapor pressure (flat surface of the same liquid) and *S* is the saturation ratio.
[src:eye-protection/aerosol] where *rp* droplet radius, *σ* surface tension of droplet, *ρ* density of liquid, *M* molar mass, *T* temperature, and *R* molar gas constant.
[src:eye-protection/aerosol] Aerosols can either be measured in-situ or with remote sensing techniques either ground-based on airborne-based.
[src:eye-protection/aerosol] Particles can deposit in the nose, mouth, pharynx and larynx (the head airways region), deeper within the respiratory tract (from the trachea to the terminal bronchioles), or in the alveolar region.
[src:eye-protection/aerosol] The location of deposition of aerosol particles within the respiratory system strongly determines the health effects of exposure to such aerosols.
[src:eye-protection/aerosol] This phenomenon led people to invent aerosol samplers that select a subset of the aerosol particles that reach certain parts of the respiratory system.
[src:eye-protection/aerosol] Examples of these subsets of the particle-size distribution of an aerosol, important in occupational health, include the inhalable, thoracic, and respirable fractions.
[src:eye-protection/aerosol] The fraction that can enter each part of the respiratory system depends on the deposition of particles in the upper parts of the airway.
[src:eye-protection/aerosol] The inhalable fraction of particles, defined as the proportion of particles originally in the air that can enter the nose or mouth, depends on external wind speed and direction and on the particle-size distribution by aerodynamic diameter.
[src:eye-protection/aerosol] The thoracic fraction is the proportion of the particles in ambient aerosol that can reach the thorax or chest region.
[src:eye-protection/aerosol] The respirable fraction is the proportion of particles in the air that can reach the alveolar region.
[src:eye-protection/aerosol] To measure the respirable fraction of particles in air, a pre-collector is used with a sampling filter.
[src:eye-protection/aerosol] The pre-collector excludes particles as the airways remove particles from inhaled air.
[src:eye-protection/aerosol] The sampling filter collects the particles for measurement.
[src:eye-protection/aerosol] It is common to use cyclonic separation for the pre-collector, but other techniques include impactors, horizontal elutriators, and large pore membrane filters.
[src:eye-protection/aerosol] Two alternative size-selective criteria, often used in atmospheric monitoring, are PM10 and PM2.5.
[src:eye-protection/aerosol] PM10 is defined by ISO as *particles which pass through a size-selective inlet with a 50% efficiency cut-off at 10 μm aerodynamic diameter* and PM2.5 as *particles which pass through a size-selective inlet with a 50% efficiency cut-off at 2.5 μm aerodynamic diameter*.
[src:eye-protection/aerosol] PM10 corresponds to the "thoracic convention" as defined in ISO 7708:1995, Clause 6; PM2.5 corresponds to the "high-risk respirable convention" as defined in ISO 7708:1995, 7.1.
[src:eye-protection/aerosol] The United States Environmental Protection Agency replaced the older standards for particulate matter based on Total Suspended Particulate with another standard based on PM10 in 1987 and then introduced standards for PM2.5 (also known as fine particulate matter) in 1997.
[src:eye-protection/alleycat-race] An **alleycat race** is an unsanctioned bicycle race.
[src:eye-protection/alleycat-race] Alley cats almost always take place in cities, and are often organized by bicycle messengers.
[src:eye-protection/alleycat-race] The informality of the organization is matched by the emphasis on taking part, rather than simple competition.
[src:eye-protection/alleycat-race] For instance, many alleycats present prizes for the last competitor to finish (sometimes known as Dead Fucking Last or DFL).
[src:eye-protection/alleycat-race] The first race to be called an 'alley cat' was held in Toronto on 30 October 1989 and continued, in its original form, around Halloween and Valentine's Day for the following five years.
[src:eye-protection/alleycat-race] In 1993, when Toronto messengers shared Alleycat stories at the first international messenger race (C.M.W.C Berlin), the name and the concept spread globally.
[src:eye-protection/alleycat-race] Regularly organized Alleycats can be found in cities across North America, Europe and Asia.
[src:eye-protection/alleycat-race] Many smaller cities with no cycle messenger population are also home to alleycats run by the burgeoning urban cyclist subculture.
[src:eye-protection/alleycat-race] Alley cats reflect the personality, contemporary environment and competitive interest of their organizers.
[src:eye-protection/alleycat-race] Races may be extremely grueling and designed to eliminate all but the fastest and best overall messengers, or less competitive and meant to be enjoyed by the local messenger community around set holidays, such as New York City's July 4 Alleycat.
[src:eye-protection/alleycat-race] Participants do not wear conventional race numbers; instead, "spoke cards", originally Tarot cards, are sometimes specially printed for the event.
[src:eye-protection/alleycat-race] Participants' number is added with a marker and are then wedged between the spokes of the rear wheel.
[src:eye-protection/alleycat-race] Spoke cards are often kept on the wheel by participants as a souvenir, who collect more over time.
[src:eye-protection/alleycat-race] Substantiating the growth of alleycat racing is difficult, given the lack of publicity and record-keeping in the community.
[src:eye-protection/alleycat-race] Some themes commonly associated with alleycats, such as the use of fixed-gear bicycles, became more popular in the later half of the 2000s.
[src:eye-protection/alleycat-race] The number of alleycats being organized also appears to be on the rise, as non-couriers begin to organize their own races.
[src:eye-protection/alleycat-race] Events featuring alleycat racing culture have seen significant expansion since 2000.
[src:eye-protection/alleycat-race] Meanwhile, events like the Bicycle Film Festival have expanded across dozens of cities and embraced many different expressions of alleycat-style bicycle culture.
[src:eye-protection/alleycat-race] Alleycat veteran and videographer Lucas Brunelle is widely credited as having pioneered the art of filming alleycat races from the first-person perspective and sharing the footage online.
[src:eye-protection/alleycat-race] YouTube currently hosts more than 1,000 videos of alleycat races, most of which have been uploaded since 2006.
[src:eye-protection/alleycat-race] On May 19, 2018, the first Citi Bike Race, was held in New York City.
[src:eye-protection/alleycat-race] The event was an alleycat style race where all participant rode bicycles from the city's bike sharing program, Citi Bike.
[src:eye-protection/alleycat-race] In the United Kingdom, organised cycle racing on public roads requires the authority of the police and the relevant sporting organisation.
[src:eye-protection/alleycat-race] However, treasure hunts and time trials are legal.
[src:eye-protection/alleycat-race] Organizers often attempt to put issues of legality in the hands of racers.
[src:eye-protection/alleycat-race] The decision to break any laws is left to the individual.
[src:eye-protection/alleycat-race] On February 24, 2008, Matt Manger-Lynch was killed in a collision with a car while participating in the 'Tour Da Chicago', a winter alleycat series.
[src:eye-protection/alleycat-race] Eyewitnesses reported that he had failed to stop for a red light.
[src:eye-protection/alleycat-race] Manger-Lynch's death prompted local news outlets to report on the phenomenon of alleycat races.
[src:eye-protection/eye-protection] Eye protection are typically separated into categories based on the style of eye wear and the hazard they are designed to reduce.
[src:eye-protection/eye-protection] There categories include: spectacles with side protection; goggles; welding helmet; welding hand shields; non-rigid helmets (hoods); face shield; and respirator face pieces.
[src:eye-protection/eye-protection] Safety glasses or spectacles, although often used as a catch-all term for all types of eye protection, specifically refers to protective equipment that closely resembles common eye wear.
[src:eye-protection/eye-protection] To meet most national standards, spectacles must include side shields to reduce the ability of debris to get behind the lenses from the side.
[src:eye-protection/eye-protection] Safety glasses can often mount insert frames to mount prescription corrective lenses for users with suboptimal vision.
[src:eye-protection/eye-protection] Such insert frames are mounted behind the protective lens.
[src:eye-protection/eye-protection] In some applications, regular eye wear, if manufactured from high-impact materials, can be worn with removable side shields.
[src:eye-protection/eye-protection] Oversized spectacles are also manufactured, designed to sit over the user's normal eye wear.
[src:eye-protection/eye-protection] Goggles are forms of protective eyewear that enclose the eye area in order to prevent particulates, infectious fluids, or chemicals from striking the eyes.
[src:eye-protection/eye-protection] Goggles come in two styles, eyecup goggles, and cover goggles.
[src:eye-protection/eye-protection] Eyecup goggles completely cover the eye socket to give all-round protection.
[src:eye-protection/eye-protection] They have adjustable or elasticized headbands and often are equipped with ventilation ports to allow air in and prevent fogging.
[src:eye-protection/eye-protection] For example, swimming goggles protect the eyes from salt or chlorine.
[src:eye-protection/eye-protection] Cover goggles are designed to be worn over eye wear.
[src:eye-protection/eye-protection] Like eyecup goggles, they have adjustable or elasticized headbands and are equipped with direct or indirect ventilation ports to allow air in and prevent fogging.
[src:eye-protection/eye-protection] While both models keep out large particles, indirect-vented goggles are better at keeping out liquids and dusts.
[src:eye-protection/eye-protection] A welding helmet is a type of headgear used when performing certain types of welding to protect the eyes, face and neck from flash burn, ultraviolet light, sparks, infrared light, and heat.
[src:eye-protection/eye-protection] A welding hand shield is a metal plate containing the same protective lens as a welding helmet with a handle on the bottom, intended to be held up in front of the face while working.
[src:eye-protection/eye-protection] Hoods (or non-rigid helmets) come with impact-resistant windows usually made of plastic or similar material.
[src:eye-protection/eye-protection] An air-supply system may also be incorporated.
[src:eye-protection/eye-protection] Hoods are made of non-rigid material for use in confined spaces and of collapsible construction for convenience in carrying and storing.
[src:eye-protection/eye-protection] A face shield is a device used to protect wearer's entire face (or part of it) from hazards such as impact, splash, heat, or glare.
[src:eye-protection/eye-protection] With face shields, as with welding helmets and hand shields, the user is periodically lifting and lowering the visor.
[src:eye-protection/eye-protection] To protect the eyes when the visor is lifted, spectacles should be worn underneath.
[src:eye-protection/eye-protection] A respirator is a device designed to protect the wearer from inhaling particulate matter, including airborne microorganisms, fumes, vapours and gases.
[src:eye-protection/eye-protection] Insects like flies, bees, and wasps can fly at high speeds and come into contact with a person's eyes.
[src:eye-protection/eye-protection] Their wings or stingers can cause irritation or even scratch the cornea, which can be painful and potentially cause long-term damage.
[src:eye-protection/eye-protection] Small projectiles and fragments generated from processes like grinding, machining, or tool or part breakage under strain (e.g., when torque is applied with hand tools, power tools, impact wrenches, or cheater bars) can have the potential to penetrate some types of protective eye-wear.
[src:eye-protection/eye-protection] In the United States the ANSI/ISEA Z87.1-2020 standard is used to certify protective eye-wear which is capable of protecting from these hazards.
[src:eye-protection/eye-protection] Debris such as dust, dirt, and small rocks can be picked up by the wind and fly into one's eyes.
[src:eye-protection/eye-protection] This can cause discomfort and potentially lead to a corneal abrasion or infection.
[src:eye-protection/eye-protection] Ultraviolet (UV) radiation from the sun can also harm a person's eyes.
[src:eye-protection/eye-protection] Prolonged exposure to UV rays can cause cataracts, macular degeneration, and other eye conditions that can lead to vision loss.
[src:eye-protection/eye-protection] A large percentage of eye injuries are caused by direct contact with chemicals.
[src:eye-protection/eye-protection] These injuries often result from an inappropriate choice of personal protective equipment that allows a chemical substance to enter from around or under protective eye equipment.
[src:eye-protection/eye-protection] Serious and irreversible damage can occur when chemical substances contact the eyes in the form of splash, mists, vapors, or fumes.
[src:eye-protection/eye-protection] When working with or around chemicals, it is important to know the location of emergency eyewash stations and how to access them with restricted vision.
[src:eye-protection/eye-protection] When fitted and worn correctly, goggles protect your eyes from hazardous substances.
[src:eye-protection/eye-protection] A face shield may be required in areas where workers are exposed to severe chemical hazards.
[src:eye-protection/eye-protection] The human eye is sensitive to intense light because it damages the retina and can even blind the individual.
[src:eye-protection/eye-protection] There are many different types of eye protection against light suited for different applications.
[src:eye-protection/eye-protection] The most common forms of eye protection against light are sunglasses.
[src:eye-protection/eye-protection] These primarily protect against UV light from the sun and help increase visibility in bright conditions.
[src:eye-protection/eye-protection] They often tend to be fashionable as well as practical.
[src:eye-protection/eye-protection] Laser protection eyewear will filter out a particular (or small range of) wavelength(s), customized to the laser being viewed.
[src:eye-protection/eye-protection] Laser protection eye wear is particularly important because of the extremely high intensity of laser light.
[src:eye-protection/eye-protection] Welding glass protects against glare and flying sparks.
[src:eye-protection/eye-protection] It is a more extreme implementation of the same idea as sunglasses, suited to the more intense light generated during welding.
[src:eye-protection/eye-protection] Arc welding goggles must be much darker than blowtorch goggles.
[src:eye-protection/eye-protection] Shades 12, 13, and 14 welding glass must be used to stare directly at the sun or a solar eclipse.
[src:eye-protection/eye-protection] These higher index shades are suitable for arc welding and therefore are suitable for solar viewing.
[src:eye-protection/eye-protection] Sunglasses will not provide sufficient protection.
